#45 2992.4  * Important: The openrc libvirtd init script is now broken up into two
#45 2992.4  * separate services: libvirtd, that solely handles the daemon, and
#45 2992.4  * libvirt-guests, that takes care of clients during shutdown/restart of the
#45 2992.4  * host. In order to reenable client handling, edit /etc/conf.d/libvirt-guests
#45 2992.4  * and enable the service and start it:
#45 2992.4  * $ rc-update add libvirt-guests
#45 2992.4  * $ rc-service libvirt-guests start
#45 2992.4  * For the basic networking support (bridged and routed networks) you don't
#45 2992.4  * need any extra software. For more complex network modes including but not
#45 2992.4  * limited to NATed network, you can enable the 'virt-network' USE flag. It
#45 2992.4  * will pull in required runtime dependencies
#45 2992.4  * If you are using dnsmasq on your system, you will have to configure
#45 2992.4  * /etc/dnsmasq.conf to enable the following settings:
#45 2992.4  * bind-interfaces
#45 2992.4  * interface or except-interface
#45 2992.4  * Otherwise you might have issues with your existing DNS server.
#45 2992.4  * For openrc users:
#45 2992.4  * Please use /etc/conf.d/libvirtd to control the '--listen' parameter for
#45 2992.4  * libvirtd.
#45 2992.4  * Use /etc/init.d/libvirt-guests to manage clients on restart/shutdown of
#45 2992.4  * the host. The default configuration will suspend and resume running kvm
#45 2992.4  * guests with 'managedsave'. This behavior can be changed under
#45 2992.4  * /etc/conf.d/libvirt-guests
#45 2992.4  * For systemd users:
#45 2992.4  * The '--listen' parameter is unavailable when libvirtd is run as a
#45 2992.4  * systemd unit.
#45 2992.4  * The configuration for the 'libvirt-guests.service' is found under
#45 2992.4  * /etc/libvirt/libvirt-guests.conf"
#45 2992.4  * If you have built libvirt with policykit support, a new group "libvirt" has
#45 2992.4  * been created. Simply add a user to the libvirt group in order to grant
#45 2992.4  * administrative access to libvirtd. Alternatively, drop a custom policykit
#45 2992.4  * rule into /etc/polkit-1/rules.d.
#45 2992.4  * If you have built libvirt without policykit support (USE=-policykit), you
#45 2992.4  * must change the unix sock group and/or perms in /etc/libvirt/libvirtd.conf
#45 2992.4  * in order to allow normal users to connect to libvirtd.
#45 2992.4  * If libvirt is built with USE=caps, libvirt will now start qemu/kvm VMs
